The most basal group of temnospondyls is the superfamily Edopoidea. Edopoids have several primitive or plesiomorphic features, including a single occipital condyle and a bone called the intertemporal that is absent in other temnospondyls. Edopoids include the Late Carboniferous genus Edops and the family Cochleosauridae. Dendrerpetontidae has also been included in Edopoidea, and is the oldest known temnospondyl family. Balanerpeton woodi is the oldest species, having been present over 330 million years ago during the Keathian which began in the Pennsylvanian. Ichthyostega was a large genus of temnospondyls which lived during the Silurian. Currently, however, it is likely that edopooids and cochleosaurids are not closely related and that they did not occur together. Additional members of the superfamily are Brancasaurus from Europe and Carrollia and Yundlella from Australia. Agnomeropsis from China has also recently been included in the superfamily Cochleosauridae, although it is currently in a problematic genus.
